Data Visualization

By: abdullah Elsayed

  • 1. Introduction
  • 2. Matplotlib

1. Introduction

Data visualization is the graphical representation of information and data. By using visual elements like charts, graphs, and maps, data visualization tools provide an accessible way to see and understand trends, outliers, and patterns in data.

In the world of Big Data, data visualization tools and technologies are essential to analyze massive amounts of information and make data-driven decision

Role of Data Visualization in data science¶

  • Data Checking and Cleaning.
    • Data visualization can be used to look for obvious errors in the dataset including nulls, random values, distinct records, the format of dates, sensibility of spatial data, and string and character encoding.

  • Data Distribution

    • Data visualization can be used to understand the distribution of the data, look for central tendencies (mean, median, and mode), understand the presence of outliers using a boxplot, check for skewness, and ever understand the impact of winsorization on data distribution. Figure 4 below illustrates how box plots can be developed to understand the presence of outliers.

  • Model Assumptions

    • Linear regression and other classification models follow certain underlying assumptions like data has to be normally distributed, the correlation between different independent variables shouldn’t exist, homoscedasticity of error terms, and many more. Hence visualizations are a key to validating some of these assumptions as well.
Python offers multiple great graphing libraries that come packed with lots of different features. No matter if you want to create interactive, live or highly customized plots python has an excellent library for you.

To get a little overview here are a few popular plotting libraries:

  • Matplotlib: low level, provides lots of freedom
  • Pandas Visualization: easy to use interface, built on Matplotlib
  • Seaborn: high-level interface, great default styles
  • ggplot: based on R’s ggplot2, uses Grammar of Graphics
  • Plotly: can create interactive plots

In [5]:
## Create plot by add fig and axes
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(6,3))  ## 6 is width,  3 is height

## Plot the data
ax.plot(x, y, color= 'lightblue' , linewidth=3)

## cstomize plot
ax.set_title('Title of the plot') ## add title
ax.set_xlabel('(X) axis') ## add label to x axis
ax.set_ylabel('(Y) axis') ## add label to y axis

## Save plot
# plt.savefig("source/name of plot.extension")
plt.show()

Line Chart

This type of chart is created by connecting a series of data points together with a solid line

When to use a Line Chart --> If you have continuous data that you would like to represent through a chart then a line chart is a good option

Usually these graphs show time series data but they can display other continuous variables like distance, for example how the level of a chemical varies with depth of soil.

In Matplotlib we can create a line chart by calling the plot method. We can also plot multiple columns in one graph, by looping through the columns we want and plotting each column on the same axis.

Plot number of employees per year

In [6]:
## prepare data
emp_count = [3, 20, 50, 200, 350, 400]
year = [2014, 2015, 2016, 2017, 2018, 2019]

## create plot
fig,ax = plt.subplots()

## plot the data and customize the line
ax.plot(year, emp_count)


plt.show()

The same previous chart with some customizations

In [7]:
## prepare data
emp_count = [3, 20, 50, 200, 350, 400]
year = [2014, 2015, 2016, 2017, 2018, 2019]

## create plot
fig,ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8,4))  ## size of figure --> width 8 and height 4

## plot the data and customize the line
ax.plot(year, emp_count,
       marker='o', ## marker for each single point on the x-axis
       linestyle='--', 
       linewidth=2, 
       color='r')


## customize ur plots
ax.set_title("Number of employees per year", fontsize=20, color='r') ## add title for the chart
ax.set_xlabel("Year", fontsize=15, color='b')  ## add label for x-axis
ax.set_ylabel("Number of emplyee", fontsize=15, color='b')  ## add label for y-axis

plt.xticks(color='b', fontsize=12)  ## also u can use x_pos, bars
plt.yticks(color='b', fontsize=12)

plt.show()

## prepare data
emp_countA = [250, 300, 325, 380, 320, 350]
emp_countB = [3, 20, 50, 200, 350, 400]
year = [2014, 2015, 2016, 2017, 2018, 2019]

## create plot
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8,4))

## plot data 
ax.plot(year, emp_countA, label='Count A')
ax.plot(year, emp_countB, label='Count B')

ax.set(title='countA vs countB per year',
      xlabel='Year',
      ylabel='emp_count')

ax.legend() ## add legends with labels
plt.show()
Also we can plot all columns in dataframe using loop
In [10]:
import pandas as pd

## prepare data
emp_countA = [250, 300, 325, 380, 320, 350]
emp_countB = [3, 20, 50, 200, 350, 400]
emp_countC = [20, 35, 60, 80, 120, 180]
year = [2014, 2015, 2016, 2017, 2018, 2019]
df = {'Year':year,'emp_countA':emp_countA, 'emp_countB':emp_countB, 'emp_countC':emp_countC }
df = pd.DataFrame(df)


fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8,4))

for col in df.columns.drop(['Year']):
    ax.plot(year, df[col], label=df[col].name)

ax.set(title='countA vs countB vs CountC per year',
      xlabel='Year',
      ylabel='emp_count')

ax.legend(loc='upper left') ## add legends with labels
plt.show()
Plot columns on multiple charts
In [11]:
## create plot
fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=3, figsize=(15,5))

## first chart
ax[0].plot(df['Year'], df['emp_countA'], color='red')
ax[0].set(title='countA per year',
      xlabel='Year',
      ylabel='emp_countA')

## second chart
ax[1].plot(df['Year'], df['emp_countB'], color='green')
ax[1].set(title='countB per year',
      xlabel='Year',
      ylabel='emp_countB')

## third chart
ax[2].plot(df['Year'], df['emp_countC'], color='orange')
ax[2].set(title='countC per year',
      xlabel='Year',
      ylabel='emp_countC')

plt.tight_layout(pad=2)
plt.show()

bar Chart

  • A bar chart displays categorical data with rectangular bars whose length or height corresponds to the value of each data point.
  • Bar charts can be visualized using vertical or horizontal bars.
  • Bar charts are best used to compare a single category of data or several.
  • Bar charts use volume to demonstrate differences between each bar. Because of this, bar charts should always start at zero. When bar charts do not start at zero, it risks users misjudging the difference between data values.

## create plot using the year and the total
fig, ax= plt.subplots(figsize=(8,4))

## customize the color based on max column
colors = ['green' if (bar == max(df['total'])) else 'darkviolet' for bar in df['total']]

## plot the data
ax.bar(df['year'], df['total'], color=colors, width=0.7, align='center') ## align maybe 'edge'


## cstomize the plot
ax.set(title='Total participation per year',
      xlabel='Year',
      ylabel='Total')
plt.xticks(rotation=20) ## rotate x-axis
plt.show()

Scatter Chart

  • A scatter plot is a data visualization that displays the values of two different variables as points. The data for each point is represented by its horizontal (x) and vertical (y) position on the visualization.

  • Use a scatter plot to determine whether or not two variables have a relationship or correlation.

  • If you have two variables that pair well together, plotting them on a scatter diagram is a great way to view their relationship and see if it’s a positive or negative correlation.

  • Avoid a scatter plot when you have too large a set of data.

y2= -5*x

## create plot
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8,4))

# plot data 
ax.scatter(x,y1, label='y1', marker= '*')
ax.scatter(x,y2, label='y2', marker= 'o')
ax.scatter(x,y3, label='y3', marker= '^')


## customization
ax.set(title='relationship of 3 variables',
      xlabel='x-axis',
      ylabel='y-axis')

plt.legend(loc='upper center')

# Annotate
plt.text(2.5, 23, "y1", horizontalalignment='left', size='medium', color='blue', weight='semibold')
plt.text(2.5, -9, "y2", horizontalalignment='left', size='medium', color='orange', weight='semibold')
plt.text(2.5, 2, "y3", horizontalalignment='left', size='medium', color='green', weight='semibold')
         
plt.show()

PIE Chart

In [33]:
## prepare data
labels = 'Frogs', 'Hogs', 'Dogs', 'Logs'
sizes = [15, 30, 45, 10]

## Create plt
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8,8))

## plot data 
ax.pie(sizes, labels=labels, shadow=True, explode=[0.1,0,0,0], autopct='%1.1f%%', startangle=90)

plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.0,1.0), fontsize='large')
plt.show()
In [61]:
## prepare data
labels = 'Frogs', 'Hogs', 'Dogs', 'Logs'
sizes = [15, 30, 45, 10]

## Create plot
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8,8))

## add colors 
colors = ['#9932cc','#bada55','#fa8072','#20b2aa']

## plot data 
patches, texts, autotexts = ax.pie(sizes, labels=labels, colors=colors, shadow=True, explode=[0.1,0,0,0], autopct='%1.1f%%', startangle=90)

## customize annotation
for text in texts:
    text.set_color('grey')
    text.set_fontsize(15)
for text in autotexts:
    text.set_color('#fff')
    text.set_fontsize(12)
    
## plt.legend(fontsize='x-large')
ax.axis('equal')  
plt.show()

box plot

  • Box plot gives statistical information about the distribution of numeric data divided into different groups. It is useful for detecting outliers within each group.

In [94]:
# prepare data
np.random.seed(42)
spread = np.random.rand(50) * 100
center = np.ones(25) * 50
flier_high = np.random.rand(10) * 100 + 100
flier_low = np.random.rand(10) * -100
data = np.concatenate((spread, center, flier_high, flier_low))

## Create plot
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8,5))

## plot data
ax.boxplot(data, showfliers=True, vert=False)

ax.set_title('Basic Plot')


plt.show()
